{"number":"3.132","name":"alpha testing","definitions":"first stage of testing before a product is considered ready for commercial or operational use"}
{"number":"3.133","name":"alphanumeric","definitions":"pertaining to data that consists of letters, digits, and usually other characters, such as punctuation marks, as well as to processes and functional units that use the data"}
{"number":"3.134","name":"ALS","definitions":"Application Layer Structure"}
{"number":"3.135","name":"alternate flow","definitions":"part of a use case that describes its alternative implementations"}
{"number":"3.136","name":"alternate key","definitions":"candidate key of an entity other than the primary key"}
{"number":"3.137","name":"alternative analysis","definitions":"a technique used to evaluate identified options in order to select which options or approaches to use to execute and perform the work of the project"}
{"number":"3.138","name":"alternatives generation","definitions":"a technique used to develop as many potential options as possible in order to identify different approaches to execute and perform the work of the project"}
{"number":"3.139","name":"analog","definitions":"pertaining to continuously variable physical quantities or to data presented in a continuous form, as well as to processes and functional units that use the data"}
{"number":"3.140","name":"analog computer","definitions":"computer whose operations are analogous to the behavior of another system and that accepts, processes, and produces analog data"}
{"number":"3.141","name":"analogous estimating","definitions":"a technique for estimating the duration or cost of an activity or a project using historical data from a similar activity or project"}
{"number":"3.142","name":"analysis","definitions":"process of studying a system by partitioning the system into parts (functions, components, or objects) and determining how the parts relate to each other2. investigation and collection phase of development that aims to specify types of users and their information needs"}
{"number":"3.143","name":"analyst","definitions":"member of the technical community who is skilled and trained to define problems and to analyze, develop, and express algorithms"}
{"number":"3.144","name":"analytic hierarchy process (AHP)","definitions":"use of matrixes to manage pair-wise relationships in decision-making"}
{"number":"3.145","name":"analytical techniques","definitions":"various techniques used to evaluate, analyze, or forecast potential outcomes based on possible variations of project or environmental variables and their relationships with other variables"}
{"number":"3.146","name":"analyzability","definitions":"degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which it is possible to assess the impact on a product or system of an intended change to one or more of its parts, or to diagnose a product for deficiencies or causes of failures, or to identify parts to be modified"}
{"number":"3.147","name":"ancestor (of a class)","definitions":"generic ancestor of the class or a parent of the class or an ancestor of a parent of the class"}
{"number":"3.148","name":"ancestral box","definitions":"box related to a specific diagram by a hierarchically consecutive sequence of one or more parent/child relationships"}
{"number":"3.149","name":"ancestral diagram","definitions":"diagram that contains an ancestral box"}
{"number":"3.150","name":"anchor point","definitions":"a milestone in software scheduling at which a major project life cycle transition occurs"}
{"number":"3.151","name":"annotate","definitions":"command used for listing the latest version of each program's source code line, along with the date, the file version it was introduced, and the person who committed it"}
{"number":"3.152","name":"annotation","definitions":"further documentation accompanying a requirement"}
{"number":"3.153","name":"announcement","definitions":"interaction (invocation) initiated by a client object, resulting in the conveyance of information from that client object to a server object, requesting a function to be performed by that server object"}
{"number":"3.154","name":"annual equivalent","definitions":"representation of a cash flow as a series of equal annual payments (at a stated interest rate) over the planning horizon."}
{"number":"3.155","name":"annual percentage rate (APR)","definitions":"nominal annual interest rate"}
{"number":"3.156","name":"annuity","definitions":"amount of a series of equal payments at regular intervals over a planning horizon"}
{"number":"3.157","name":"anomaly","definitions":"condition that deviates from expectations, based on requirements specifications, design documents, user documents, or standards, or from someone's perceptions or experiences"}
{"number":"3.158","name":"ANSI","definitions":"American National Standards Institute."}
{"number":"3.159","name":"anticipatory buffering","definitions":"buffering technique in which data are stored in a buffer in anticipation of a need for the data"}
{"number":"3.160","name":"anticipatory paging","definitions":"storage allocation technique in which pages are transferred from auxiliary storage to main storage in anticipation of a need for those pages"}
{"number":"3.161","name":"AOA","definitions":"analysis of alternatives"}
{"number":"3.162","name":"AON","definitions":"Activity-on-No"}
{"number":"3.163","name":"AP(I)","definitions":"Application Process (Invocation)"}
{"number":"3.164","name":"aperiodic task","definitions":"task activated on demand"}
{"number":"3.165","name":"API","definitions":"Application Program Interface"}
{"number":"3.166","name":"applicability to a functional domain","definitions":"the ability of an FSM method to take into account the characteristics of functional user requirements (FUR) which are pertinent to FSM in a functional domain"}
{"number":"3.167","name":"application","definitions":"system for collecting, saving, processing, and presenting data by means of a computer"}
{"number":"3.168","name":"application administration function","definitions":"functions performed by users which include installation, configuration, application backup, maintenance (patching and upgrading) and de-installation"}
{"number":"3.169","name":"application architecture","definitions":"architecture including the architectural structure and rules (e.g. common rules and constraints) that constrains a specific member product within a product line"}
{"number":"3.170","name":"application area","definitions":"a category of projects that have common components significant in such projects, but are not needed or present in all projects. Application areas are usually defined in terms of either the product (i.e., by similar technologies or production methods) or the type of customer (i.e., internal versus external, government versus commercial) or industry sector (i.e., utilities, automotive, aerospace, information technologies, etc.) Application areas can overlap."}
{"number":"3.171","name":"application asset","definitions":"output of a specific application engineering process (e.g. application realization) that can be exploited in other lifecycle processes of application engineering and can be adapted as a domain asset based on a product management decision"}
{"number":"3.172","name":"application assets in requirements","definitions":"application-specific artifacts produced during application requirements engineering, such as application requirements specifications and application requirements models"}
{"number":"3.173","name":"application boundary","definitions":"the border between the application and its environment of other applications and users"}
{"number":"3.174","name":"application design","definitions":"process of application engineering where a single application architecture conforming to the domain architecture is derived"}
{"number":"3.175","name":"application engineering","definitions":"process of constructing or refining application systems by reusing assets"}
{"number":"3.176","name":"application engineering process","definitions":"processes for developing a member product in a product line"}
{"number":"3.177","name":"application frameworks","definitions":"subsystem design made up of a collection of abstract and concrete classes and interfaces between them"}
{"number":"3.178","name":"application function point count","definitions":"a count that provides a measure of the functionality the application provides to the end-user"}
{"number":"3.179","name":"application functional size","definitions":"measure of the functionality that an application provides to the user, determined by the application function point count"}
{"number":"3.180","name":"application generator","definitions":"code generator that produces programs to solve one or more problems in a particular application area"}
{"number":"3.181","name":"application management","definitions":"domain responsible for all of the tasks and activities that are aimed at managing, supporting, maintaining, and renewing existing applications and related data structures"}
{"number":"3.182","name":"application management organization","definitions":"organizational unit that is responsible for application management for one or more applications"}
{"number":"3.183","name":"application object","definitions":"component that is directly related to or forms part of an application"}
{"number":"3.184","name":"application portfolio","definitions":"collection of applications managed by an application management organization or an entity within that application management organization"}
{"number":"3.185","name":"application problem","definitions":"problem submitted by an end user and requiring information processing for its solution. ISO/IEC 2382:2015, Information technology — Vocabulary]"}
{"number":"3.186","name":"application realization","definitions":"process of application engineering that develops application assets, some of which can be derived from domain assets, and member products based on the application architecture and the sets of application assets and domain assets"}
{"number":"3.187","name":"application requirements analysis","definitions":"subprocess that understands all application specific requirements, scrutinizes incorrect and inconsistent application requirements through modelling, and then analyses and negotiates application requirements that cannot be satisfied through the domain requirements"}
{"number":"3.188","name":"application requirements elicitation","definitions":"subprocess for identifying stakeholders relevant to an application, eliciting application specific requirements, and binding the appropriate variants"}
{"number":"3.189","name":"application requirements management","definitions":"subprocess that manages traceability and changes on application requirements"}
{"number":"3.190","name":"application requirements specification","definitions":"subprocess that documents the application specific requirements and integrates it with the domain requirements specification whose variants are bound"}
{"number":"3.191","name":"application requirements verification and validation","definitions":"subprocess that confirms that the application specific requirements are consistent and feasible and ensures that the bound variants satisfy the specific product's requirements"}
{"number":"3.192","name":"application software","definitions":"software designed to help users perform particular tasks or handle particular types of problems, as distinct from software that controls the computer itself"}
{"number":"3.193","name":"application specific integrated circuit (ASIC)","definitions":"integrated circuit customized for a particular use"}
{"number":"3.194","name":"application-oriented language","definitions":"computer language with facilities or notations applicable primarily to a single application area"}
{"number":"3.195","name":"application-specific requirements","definitions":"requirements specific to an application or requirements not covered in domain requirements"}
{"number":"3.196","name":"applying leads and lags","definitions":"a technique that is used to adjust the amount of time between predecessor and successor activities"}
{"number":"3.197","name":"apportioned effort","definitions":"an activity where effort is allotted proportionately across certain discrete efforts and not divisible into discrete efforts"}
{"number":"3.198","name":"appraisal findings","definitions":"results of an appraisal that identify the most important issues, problems, or opportunities for process improvement within the appraisal scope"}
{"number":"3.199","name":"appraisal participants","definitions":"members of the organizational unit who participate in providing information during an appraisal"}
{"number":"3.200","name":"appraisal team leader","definitions":"person who leads the activities of an appraisal and has satisfied qualification criteria for experience, knowledge, and skills defined by the appraisal method"}
{"number":"3.201","name":"appropriateness recognizability","definitions":"degree to which users can recognize whether a product or system is appropriate for their needs"}
{"number":"3.202","name":"approval","definitions":"written notification, by an authorized representative, that an information item appears to satisfy requirements and is complete"}
