{"number":"3.3151","name":"prohibition","definitions":"prescription that a particular behavior must not occur"}
{"number":"3.3152","name":"project","definitions":"endeavor with defined start and finish criteria undertaken to create a product or service in accordance with specified resources and requirements"}
{"number":"3.3153","name":"project balance","definitions":"representation, as a series of cash amounts at regular intervals, of the cumulative to-date value of an alternativ"}
{"number":"3.3154","name":"project calendar","definitions":"a calendar that identifies working days and shifts that are available for scheduled activities"}
{"number":"3.3155","name":"project charter","definitions":"a document issued by the project initiator or sponsor that formally authorizes the existence of a project, and provides the project manager with the authority to apply organizational resources to project activities"}
{"number":"3.3156","name":"project communications management","definitions":"Project communications management includes the processes that are required to ensure timely and appropriate planning, collection, creation, distribution, storage, retrieval, management, control, monitoring, and the ultimate disposition of project information"}
{"number":"3.3157","name":"project control","definitions":"activities concerned with monitoring the progress of a project, its direction, quality, and resource utilization, as compared with project plan"}
{"number":"3.3158","name":"project cost management","definitions":"Project cost management includes the processes involved in planning, estimating, budgeting, financing, funding, managing, and controlling costs so that the project can be completed within the approved budget"}
{"number":"3.3159","name":"project file","definitions":"central repository of material pertinent to a project"}
{"number":"3.3160","name":"project function point count","definitions":"the size of a development project or an enhancement project expressed in function points"}
{"number":"3.3161","name":"project funding requirements","definitions":"forecast project costs to be paid for that are derived from the cost baseline for total or periodic requirements, including projected expenditures plus anticipated liabilities"}
{"number":"3.3162","name":"project governance","definitions":"the alignment of project objectives with the strategy of the larger organization by the project sponsor and project team. A project's governance is defined by and must fit within the larger context of the program or organization sponsoring it, but is separate from organizational governance"}
{"number":"3.3163","name":"project human resource management","definitions":"Project Human Resource Management includes the processes that organize, manage, and lead the project team"}
{"number":"3.3164","name":"project initiation","definitions":"launching a process that can result in the authorization of a new project"}
{"number":"3.3165","name":"project integration management","definitions":"Project integration management includes the processes and activities needed to identify, define, combine, unify, and coordinate the various processes and project management activities within the project management process groups"}
{"number":"3.3166","name":"project life cycle","definitions":"the series of phases that a project passes through from its initiation to its closure"}
{"number":"3.3167","name":"project management (PM)","definitions":"the application of knowledge, skills, tools, and techniques to project activities to meet the project requirements"}
{"number":"3.3168","name":"Project Management Body of Knowledge (PMBOK®)","definitions":"An inclusive term that describes the sum of knowledge within the profession of project management. As with other professions, such as law, medicine, and accounting, the body of knowledge rests with the practitioners and academics that apply and advance it. The complete project management body of knowledge includes proven traditional practices that are widely applied and innovative practices that are emerging in the profession. The body of knowledge includes both published and unpublished materials. This body of knowledge is constantly evolving"}
{"number":"3.3169","name":"project management information system (PMIS)","definitions":"an information system consisting of the tools and techniques used to gather, integrate, and disseminate the outputs of project management processes. It is used to support all aspects of the project from initiating through closing, and can include both manual and automated systems"}
{"number":"3.3170","name":"project management knowledge area","definitions":"an identified area of project management defined by its knowledge requirements and described in terms of its component processes, practices, inputs, outputs, tools, and techniques"}
{"number":"3.3171","name":"project management office (PMO)","definitions":"an organizational structure that standardizes the project-related governance processes and facilitates the sharing of resources, methodologies, tools and techniques"}
{"number":"3.3172","name":"project management plan","definitions":"the document that describes how the project will be executed, monitored, and controlled"}
{"number":"3.3173","name":"project management process group","definitions":"a logical grouping of project management inputs, tools and techniques, and outputs. The project management process groups include initiating processes, planning processes, executing processes, monitoring and controlling processes, and closing processes. Project management process groups are not project phases"}
{"number":"3.3174","name":"project management software","definitions":"applications specifically designed to aid the project management team with planning, monitoring, and controlling the project, including cost estimating, scheduling, collaboration, and risk analysis"}
{"number":"3.3175","name":"project management staff","definitions":"the members of the project team who perform project management activities such as schedule, communications, risk management, etc."}
{"number":"3.3176","name":"project management system","definitions":"the aggregation of the processes, tools, techniques, methodologies, resources, and procedures to manage a project"}
{"number":"3.3177","name":"project management team","definitions":"the members of the project team who are directly involved in project management activities. On some smaller projects, the project management team may include virtually all of the project team members"}
{"number":"3.3178","name":"project manager (PM)","definitions":"the person assigned by the performing organization to lead the team that is responsible for achieving the project objectives"}
{"number":"3.3179","name":"project organization chart","definitions":"a document that graphically depicts the project team members and their interrelationships for a specific project"}
{"number":"3.3180","name":"project performance","definitions":"derived measure that gives an indication of some attribute associated with how well, how quickly, how effectively, or how efficiently a project is carried out"}
{"number":"3.3181","name":"project phase","definitions":"a collection of logically related project activities that culminates in the completion of one or more deliverables"}
{"number":"3.3182","name":"project plan","definitions":"document that describes the technical and management approach to be followed for a project"}
{"number":"3.3183","name":"project planning","definitions":"activities concerned with the specification of the components, timing, resources, and procedures of a project"}
{"number":"3.3184","name":"project portfolio","definitions":"collection of projects that addresses the strategic objectives of the organization"}
{"number":"3.3185","name":"project procurement management","definitions":"Project procurement management includes the processes necessary to purchase or acquire products, services, or results needed from outside the project team"}
{"number":"3.3186","name":"project quality management","definitions":"Project quality management includes the processes and activities of the performing organization that determine quality policies, objectives, and responsibilities so that the project will satisfy the needs for which it was undertaken"}
{"number":"3.3187","name":"project resource constraint","definitions":"limitation or restraint placed on resource usage, such as what resource skills or disciplines are available and the amount of a given resource available during a specified time frame"}
{"number":"3.3188","name":"project risk","definitions":"risk related to the management of a project"}
{"number":"3.3189","name":"project risk management","definitions":"project risk management includes the processes of conducting risk management planning, identification, analysis, response planning, and controlling risk on a project"}
{"number":"3.3190","name":"project risk profile","definitions":"project's current and historical risk-related information; a compendium or aggregate of all of the individual risk profiles in a project"}
{"number":"3.3191","name":"project schedule","definitions":"an output of a schedule model that presents linked activities with planned dates, durations, milestones, and resources"}
{"number":"3.3192","name":"project schedule network diagram","definitions":"a graphical display of the logical relationships among the project schedule activities"}
